You could add additional unit tests make this work complete. For example, what would happen if `getHeader` is requested to get a header that has never been passed?

Overall you are testing the relationship between `getHeader` and `putHeader` (By the way, this relatioship is called a "property" in some circles). So no matter what header is passed to putHeader, it should always be returned by getHeader. What about this:
```
String randomHeaderKey = "Header - " + System.currentTimeMillis();
String randomHeaderValue = "Value - " + System.currentTimeMillis();

AafRequestWrapper af= new AafRequestWrapper(mockRequest);
assertEquals(af.getHeader(randomHeaderKey),randomHeaderValue);
```
This guarantees that no matter the header passed, it's always returned when calling getHeader. Now having said that, a request is supposed to be immutable. So why not just removing `putHeader` and add the header in the constructor of the AafRequestWrapper?

The next use case is what if the header has never been passed to `putHeader`? You should ensure that `getHeader` returns the expected value (probably a null but this has to be verified). Ideally you should not return nulls, but the request wrapper API is done that way. Maybe a `getHeaderOption` could be added to AafRequestWrapper and then used in the filter?

Finally, to reduce boilder plate, a factory function for a mocked HttpServletRequest could be created:
```
private HttpServletRequest makeMockedHttpServletRequest(
  Map<String, String> headers
) {
  HttpServletRequest mockRequest = createMock(HttpServletRequest.class);
  headers.forEach((k, v) -> 
    expect(mockRequest.getHeader(k))
      .andReturn(v)
      .anyTimes()
  )
  return mockRequest;
}
```

Sorry for the long post, your change made me thinking a bit :)
